Experiments 1 & 2: Reaction Time Analyses

Owen Morgan

June 25, 2024

Summary

All p-values two-sided.

1,958 combined participants (860 left handers, 307 mixed handers, and 791 right handers) met inclusion criteria for experiments 1 or 2 (E1: n = 844 [331, 135, 378]; E2: n = 1,114 [529, 172, 413]).

Categorical handedness

Primary: EHI +/-40

Combining experiments, LVF global>local bias was significantly reduced in left handers ( = 860, EHI <= -40) compared to right handers ( = 791, EHI >= +40; difference between groups = 16.01ms, 95% CI [8.58, 23.51], (196,641.1) = 4.21, < .0001, two-sided) . Right handers showed 35.84ms LVF global>local bias (95% CI [30.51, 41.16], (196,641.2) = 13.19, < .0001, two-sided), and left handers showed only 19.79ms LVF global>local bias (95% CI [14.55, 25.03], (196,641.0) = 7.41, < .0001, two-sided). The interaction of field by level by handedness did not differ significantly between experiments (difference = 9.0ms greater in Experiment 2, 95% CI [-5.92, 23.96], (196,642.0) = 1.18, = .24).

Within the local level, left handers showed reversed hemifield bias, in the direction predicted by AAH: right handers responded faster to local targets in the RVF than LVF by 15.46ms (95% CI [11.55, 19.17], (196,642.6) = 7.91, < .0001), whereas left handers responded faster to local targets in the LVF than RVF by 5.00ms (95%CI [1.26, 8.74], (196,642.4) = 2.62, p = .009, two-sided; difference = 16.05, 95% CI [8.58, 23.51], (196,641.1) = 4.21, < .0001, two-sided). The effect of handedness on local hemifield bias did not differ significantly between experiments (difference = 3.20ms greater in Experiment 1, 95% CI [-7.47, 13.88], (196,642.5) = 0.59, = .56, two-sided.

Exploratory: EHI +/-100

Limiting analysis to strong left and right handers with EHI scores of {\(\pm\)}100, left handers LVF>RVF global bias was reduced by 20.49ms (95% CI [9.05, 31.93], (83,094.7) = 3.51, = .0005, two-sided). Both groups showed significant LVF global>local bias: for right handers, the effect size was 32.68ms (95% CI [24.78 ,40.57], (83,095.0) = 8.11, < .0001, two-sided); for left handers, only 12.19ms (95% CI [3.90, 20.47], (83,094.4) = 2.88, = .004, two-sided). The interaction of field by level by handedness did not differ significantly between experiments (difference = 6.03ms greater in Experiment 1, 95% CI [-16.86, 28.92], (83,094.7) = 0.52, = .61).

Within the local level, left handers showed reversed hemifield bias: right handers responded faster to local targets in the RVF than LVF by 11.86ms (95% CI [6.21, 17.51], (83,095.4) = 4.11, < .0001, two-sided), whereas left handers responded faster to local targets in the LVF than RVF by 12.99ms (95% CI [7.06, 18.91], (83,094.9) = 4.30 < .0001, two-sided; difference = 24.85ms, 95% CI [16.66, 33.04], (83,095.2) = 5.95, < .0001, two-sided). The effect of handedness on local hemifield bias did not differ significantly between experiments (difference = 13.78ms greater in Experiment 1, 95% CI [-2.61, 30.16], (83,095.1) = 1.65, = .10, two-sided).

Continuous handedness

Combining experiments, left handedness predicted reduced LVF global>local bias (0.097ms per EHI unit, 95% CI [0.054, 0.141], (233,104.7) = 4.39, < .0001, two-sided). Strong right handers (EHI = +100) showed estimated LVF global>local bias of 37.03ms (95% CI [31.47, 42.58], (233,104.9) = 13.06, < .0001, two-sided), and strong left handers (EHI = -100) showed estimated LVF global>local bias of 17.54ms (95% CI [12.02, 23.07], (233,104.5) = 6.22, < .0001, two-sided). The interaction of field by level by handedness did not differ significantly between experiments (difference = 0.063ms per EHI unit, 95% CI [-0.024, 0.15], \(\chi^2(1)\) = 1.99, = .16, two-sided).

Within the local level, left handedness predicted reversed hemifield bias (0.123ms per EHI unit, 95% CI [0.092, 0.154], (233,106.3) = 7.76, < .0001, two-sided). Strong right handers (EHI +100) showed estimated RVF local bias of 18.31 (95% CI [14.34, 22.28], (233,106.6) = 9.03, < .0001, two-sided), whereas strong left handers (EHI -100) showed estimated LVF local bias of 6.33ms (95% CI [2.38, 10.28], (233,106.1) = 3.14, = .002, two-sided). The effect of handedness on local hemifield bias did not differ between experiments (difference = 0.00ms per EHI unit, 95% CI [-0.063, 0.062], (233,106.2) = 0.01, p = .99, two-sided).

EHI

Stats

Test for an effect of experiment on the interaction of field by level, and on the effect of field (local).

RT ~ field * level * handedness * experiment + (1|subject) + (1|shape)
